ng the about icon in the top right corner loads this page.\"),z()()(),N(95,\"h3\"),H(96,\"List\"),z(),N(97,\"h4\"),H(98,\" Only List Earthquakes Shown on Map \"),z(),N(99,\"p\"),H(100,\" When the \"),N(101,\"b\"),H(102,\"Only List Earthquakes Shown on Map\"),z(),H(103,\" option is selected, the earthquakes in the list are filtered based on the map extents. \"),z(),N(104,\"h4\"),H(105,\"List Format\"),z(),N(106,\"p\"),H(107,\"Choose a custom display for the earthquakes in the list:\"),z(),N(108,\"ul\")(109,\"li\"),H(110,\"Magnitude [default]\"),z(),N(111,\"li\"),H(112,\"DYFI\"),z(),N(113,\"li\"),H(114,\"ShakeMap\"),z(),N(115,\"li\"),H(116,\"PAGER\"),z()(),N(117,\"h4\"),H(118,\"List Sort Order\"),z(),N(119,\"p\"),H(120,\"Choose the order to display the earthquakes in the list:\"),z(),N(121,\"ul\")(122,\"li\"),H(123,\"Newest first [default]\"),z(),N(124,\"li\"),H(125,\"Oldest first\"),z(),N(126,\"li\"),H(127,\"Largest magnitude first\"),z(),N(128,\"li\"),H(129,\"Smallest magnitude first\"),z()(),N(130,\"h4\"),H(131,\"Earthquakes\"),z(),N(132,\"ul\")(133,\"li\"),H(134,\"List items in bold are magnitude 4.5 and greater.\"),z(),N(135,\"li\"),H(136,' List items in red bold text have been identified as \"significant\", based on a combination of magnitude, PAGER alert level, and the number of Did You Feel It? responses. '),z(),N(137,\"li\"),H(138,' Selecting an earthquake in the list will highlight the event in the list and on the map. It will also open a pop-up with basic information for that event. A \"button\" will appear for DYFI, ShakeMap, Pager, and a tsunami message if these products are available. '),z()(),N(139,\"h4\"),H(140,\"Downloads\"),z(),N(141,\"ul\")(142,\"li\"),H(143,\"The download link is found at the bottom of the list.\"),z(),N(144,\"li\"),H(145,\" Downloads are available in the following formats: ATOM, CSV, GeoJSON, GeoJSONP, KML and QuakeML. Complete descriptions of the following formats are available on the \"),N(146,\"a\",8),H(147,\" USGS Realtime Feeds site\"),z(),H(148,\". \"),z(),N(149,\"li\"),H(150,\" The CSV format is compatible with Microsoft Excel and other spreadsheet software. Open Excel and choose the \\u201CImport\\u2026\\u201D option. Make sure it is using the \\u201Ccomma-delimited with quotes for strings\\u201D format. \"),z(),N(151,\"li\"),H(152,\" Downloading a list of earthquakes will download the worldwide list of earthquakes not just those in the map view. See \"),N(153,\"a\",9),H(154,\"Earthquake Search and Web Service API Documentation.\"),z()()(),N(155,\"h3\"),H(156,\"Map\"),z(),N(157,\"h4\"),H(158,\"Display\"),z(),N(159,\"dl\")(160,\"dt\"),H(161,\"Projection\"),z(),N(162,\"dd\"),H(163,\" The earthquake map projection is Web Mercator. \"),z(),N(164,\"dt\"),H(165,\"Reference Model\"),z(),N(166,\"dd\"),H(167,\" The reference model is WGS-84. \"),z(),N(168,\"dt\"),H(169,\"Software\"),z(),N(170,\"dd\"),H(171,\" Interactive map interface powered by Leaflet. \"),z()(),N(172,\"h4\"),H(173,\"Markers\"),z(),N(174,\"dl\")(175,\"dt\"),H(176,\"Shape\"),z(),N(177,\"dd\"),H(178,\" Earthquakes are plotted on the map as circles and non-earthquakes are plotted as diamonds (in most browsers). For users of older browsers, all events may be plotted as squares. \"),z(),N(179,\"dt\"),H(180,\"Size\"),z(),N(181,\"dd\"),H(182,\" Earthquake sizes are relative to the magnitude of the seismic event. The markers will scale depending on your device type and the zoom level of the map. \"),z(),N(183,\"dt\"),H(184,\"Color\"),z(),N(185,\"dd\"),H(186,\" Earthquake colors are relative to the age of the earthquake (red = past hour, orange = past day, yellow = past week, and white = older than past week). \"),z(),N(187,\"dt\"),H(188,\"Highlight\"),z(),N(189,\"dd\"),H(190,' Selecting an earthquake marker on the map will highlight the marker on the map and in the list. It will also open a pop up with basic information for that event. A \"button\" will appear for DYFI, ShakeMap, Pager, and a tsunami message if these products are available. '),z()(),N(191,\"h4\"),H(192,\"Controls\"),z(),N(193,\"dl\")(194,\"dt\"),H(195,\"Plus/ Minus\"),z(),N(196,\"dd\"),H(197,\" Click the plus or minus control to zoom in or out, respectively. \"),z(),N(198,\"dt\"),H(199,\"Zoom to Region\"),z(),N(200,\"dd\"),H(201,\" Click the globe icon to drop down a menu with preset locations. \"),z()(),N(202,\"h4\"),H(203,\"Interactions\"),z(),N(204,\"dl\")(205,\"dt\"),H(206,\"Zoom\"),z(),N(207,\"dd\"),H(208,\" Use the keyboard plus and minus keys, map controls (+,-), box zoom tool (magnifying glass), mouse scroll wheel, or double click the map to zoom. There is also a shift+click+drag zoom option on desktop \"),z(),N(209,\"dt\"),H(210,\"Pan\"),z(),N(211,\"dd\"),H(212,\" Click and drag, or use shift+arrow keys (left,right,up,down) to pan the map. \"),z(),N(213,\"dt\"),H(214,\"Select\"),z(),N(215,\"dd\"),H(216,' Click on an event marker to open a pop-up summary of the event (bottom-left corner of screen). Click the \"X\" in the upper-right corner of the event summary to close the pop-up. '),z(),N(217,\"dt\"),H(218,\"Hover\"),z(),N(219,\"dd\"),H(220,\" Hover over a U.S. fault, when the fault layer is visible, to display a tooltip with the fault name (view Settings > Map Layers > U.S. Faults for details). \"),z()(),N(221,\"h4\"),H(222,\"Map Layers\"),z(),N(223,\"p\"),H(224,\"Choose from one of two base maps:\"),z(),N(225,\"ul\")(226,\"li\"),H(227,\"Ocean\"),z(),N(228,\"li\"),H(229,\"Topography [default]\"),z()(),N(230,\"p\"),H(231,\"You can enable/ disable any of the overlays on the map:\"),z(),N(232,\"ul\")(233,\"li\"),H(234,\"Plate Boundaries [default=ON]\"),z(),N(235,\"li\"),H(236,\"Population Density\"),z(),N(237,\"li\"),H(238,\"U.S. Faults\"),z(),N(239,\"li\"),H(240,\"U.S. Hazards\"),z()(),N(241,\"dl\")(242,\"dt\"),H(243,\"Ocean\"),z(),N(244,\"dd\")(245,\"p\"),H(246,' This layer is from an Esri GIS service titled \"'),N(247,\"a\",10),H(248,\"World Ocean Base\"),z(),H(249,'\". This layer is designed to be used as a basemap by marine GIS professionals and as a reference map by anyone interested in ocean data. '),z()(),N(250,\"dt\"),H(251,\"Topography\"),z(),N(252,\"dd\")(253,\"p\"),H(254,' This layer is a hybrid showing a mix of data from an Esri GIS service titled \"'),N(255,\"a\",11),H(256,\"World Street Map\"),z(),H(257,'\" and the \"'),N(258,\"a\",12),H(259,\"USGS National Map\"),z(),H(260,'\". '),z()(),N(261,\"dt\"),H(262,\"Plate Boundaries\"),z(),N(263,\"dd\")(264,\"p\"),H(265,\" These data were constructed as part of the USGS \"),N(266,\"a\",13),H(267,\" Seismicity of the Earth Map Series\"),z(),H(268,\", modified from the \"),N(269,\"a\",14),H(270,\"Peter Bird Plate Boundary Model\"),z(),H(271,\" (Bird, G^3, 2003). \"),z()(),N(272,\"dt\"),H(273,\"Population Density\"),z(),N(274,\"dd\")(275,\"p\"),H(276,\" These data orginated from the \"),N(277,\"a\",15),H(278,\"LandScan 2018\\xA9 dataset\"),z(),H(279,\" and are displayed here as tiled imagery in compliance with the \"),N(280,\"a\",16),H(281,\"LandScan usage license\"),z(),H(282,\". \"),z(),N(283,\"p\"),H(284,\" \\xA9Oak Ridge National Laboratory. Amy N. Rose, Jacob J. McKee, Marie L. Urban, Edward A. Bright, Kelly M. Sims. \"),z(),N(285,\"ul\")(286,\"li\"),H(287,\"TY - DATA\"),z(),N(288,\"li\"),H(289,\"AU - Rose, Amy N.\"),z(),N(290,\"li\"),H(291,\"AU - McKee, Jacob J.\"),z(),N(292,\"li\"),H(293,\"AU - Urban, Marie L.\"),z(),N(294,\"li\"),H(295,\"AU - Bright, Eddie A.\"),z(),N(296,\"li\"),H(297,\"AU - Sims, Kelly M.\"),z(),N(298,\"li\"),H(299,\"PY - 2019\"),z(),N(300,\"li\"),H(301,\"TI - LandScan 2018\"),z(),N(302,\"li\"),H(303,\"CY - Oak Ridge, TN\"),z(),N(304,\"li\"),H(305,\"PB - Oak Ridge National Laboratory\"),z(),N(306,\"li\"),H(307,\"SE - July 1, 2019\"),z(),N(308,\"li\"),H(309,\"T3 - LandScan\"),z(),N(310,\"li\"),H(311,\"ET - 2018\"),z(),N(312,\"li\"),H(313,\"RI - global\"),z(),N(314,\"li\"),H(315,\"C1 - CY 2018\"),z(),N(316,\"li\"),H(317,\"C3 - digital raster data\"),z(),N(318,\"li\"),H(319,`AB - Using an innovative approach with Geographic Information System and Remote Sensing, ORNL's LandScan\\xA9 is the community standard for global population distribution. At approximately 1 km resolution (30\" X 30\"), LandScan is the finest resolution global population distribution data available and represents an ambient population (average over 24 hours). The LandScan algorithm, an R&D 100 Award Winner, uses spatial data and imagery analysis technologies and a multi-variable dasymetric modeling approach to disaggregate census counts within an administrative boundary. Since no single population distribution model can account for the differences in spatial data availability, quality, scale, and accuracy as well as the differences in cultural settlement practices, LandScan population distribution models are tailored to match the data conditions and geographical nature of each individual country and region.`),z(),N(320,\"li\"),H(321,\"RN - When using the LandScan data in publications, please insert this statement as appropriate: \\u201CThis product was made utilizing the LandScan 2018\\xA9 High Resolution Global Population Data Set copyrighted by UT-Battelle, LLC, operator of Oak Ridge National Laboratory under Contract No. DE-AC05-00OR22725 with the United States Department of Energy. The United States Government has certain rights in this Data Set. Neither UT-BATTELLE, LLC NOR THE UNITED STATES DEPARTMENT OF ENERGY, NOR ANY OF THEIR EMPLOYEES, MAKES ANY WARRANTY, EXPRESS OR IMPLIED, OR ASSUMES ANY LEGAL LIABILITY OR RESPONSIBILITY FOR THE ACCURACY, COMPLETENESS, OR USEFULNESS OF THE DATA SET.\\u201D\"),z(),N(322,\"li\"),H(323,\"UR - \"),N(324,\"a\",17),H(325,\"https://landscan.ornl.gov/\"),z()()()(),N(326,\"dt\"),H(327,\"U.S. Faults\"),z(),N(328,\"dd\")(329,\"p\"),H(330,\" The data used for these features were acquired from the \"),N(331,\"a\",18),H(332,\"Hazard Faults Database for the United States\"),z(),H(333,\". See the \"),N(334,\"a\",19),H(335,\" Quaternary Fault and Fold Database of the United States\"),z(),H(336,\" for more information. \"),z(),N(337,\"h4\",20),H(338,\" Known hazardous faults and fault zones in California and Nevada \"),z(),N(339,\"p\"),H(340,\" The \"),N(341,\"a\",21),H(342,\" known active fault segments in California and Nevada can be seen in Figure 25\"),z(),H(343,\" of \"),N(344,\"a\",22),H(345,\" USGS Open-File Report 96-532: National Seismic Hazard Maps, June 1996: Documentation\"),z(),H(346,\" by Arthur Frankel, Charles Mueller, Theodore Barnhard, David Perkins, E.V. Leyendecker, Nancy Dickman, Stanley Hanson, and Margaret Hopper. \"),z(),N(347,\"p\"),H(348,\" For northern California, the potential sources of earthquakes larger than magnitude 6 are documented in \"),N(349,\"a\",23),H(350,\" Open-File Report 96-705: Database of Potential Sources for Earthquakes Larger than Magnitude 6 in Northern California\"),z(),H(351,\" by the Working Group on Northern California Earthquake Potential (chaired by Jim Lienkaemper). \"),z(),N(352,\"p\"),H(353,\" For the state as a whole, see \"),N(354,\"a\",24),H(355,\" USGS Open-File Report 96-706: Probabilistic seismic hazard assessment for the State of California\"),z(),H(356,\" by Petersen, M. D., Bryant, W.A., Cramer, C.H., Cao, T., Reichle, M.S., Frankel, A.D., Lienkaemper, J.J., McCrory, P.A., and Schwartz, D.P, 1996 (published jointly as \"),N(357,\"a\",25),H(358,\" California Division of Mines and Geology Open-File Report 96-08\"),z(),H(359,\"). The faults and fault zones described in these reports are known to have been active in the last 2 million years and are thought to pose a measurable hazard. \"),z(),N(360,\"p\"),H(361,\" For California the faults on the individual zoomed-in and special maps come from the three categories of faults believed to have been active in the last 700,000 years shown on the \\u201CPreliminary Fault Activity Map of California\\u201D by C.W. Jennings (1992, California Division of Mines and Geology Open-File Report 92-03). This map has been superseded by Jennings, C.W., 1994, Fault activity map of California and adjacent areas, with locations and ages of recent volcanic eruptions: California Division of Mines and Geology, Geologic Data Map No. 6, map scale 1:750,000. \"),z(),N(362,\"p\"),H(363,\" For Nevada the faults on the individual zoomed-in and special maps come from USGS Open-File Report 96-532 mentioned above. \"),z(),N(364,\"p\"),H(365,\" For more information on files and images discussed above visit the \"),N(366,\"a\",26),H(367,\"1996 Hazard Maps Documentation Page\"),z(),H(368,\". \"),z()(),N(369,\"dt\"),H(370,\"U.S. Hazards\"),z(),N(371,\"dd\")(372,\"p\"),H(373,\" US hazard is from the \"),N(374,\"a\",27),H(375,\"USGS Seismic Hazard Mapping Project (NSHM)\"),z()()()(),N(376,\"h3\"),H(377,\"Settings\"),z(),N(378,\"h4\",20),H(379,\" Auto Update \"),z(),N(380,\"p\"),H(381,\" This option will automatically update the earthquake data every minute. Auto update defaults to ON for both desktop and mobile devices. \"),z(),N(382,\"h4\",20),H(383,\"Feeds\"),z(),N(384,\"p\"),H(385,\" The default feed is set to display earthquakes of magnitude 2.5 and greater during the past 24 hrs (1 Day, Magnitude 2.5+). You can choose from the following options: \"),z(),N(386,\"ul\")(387,\"li\"),H(388,\"1 Day, Magnitude 2.5+ [default]\"),z(),N(389,\"li\"),H(390,\"1 Day, All Magnitudes\"),z(),N(391,\"li\"),H(392,\"7 Days, Magnitude 4.5+\"),z(),N(393,\"li\"),H(394,\"7 Days, Magnitude 2.5+\"),z(),N(395,\"li\"),H(396,\"7 Days, All Magnitudes\"),z(),N(397,\"li\"),H(398,\"30 Days, Significant Worldwide\"),z(),N(399,\"li\"),H(400,\"30 Days, Magnitude 4.5+\"),z(),N(401,\"li\"),H(402,\"30 Days, Magnitude 2.5+\"),z(),N(403,\"li\"),H(404,\"30 Days, All Magnitudes\"),z()(),N(405,\"h4\",20),H(406,\" Search Earthquake Archives \"),z(),N(407,\"p\"),H(408,\" Click \"),N(409,\"b\"),H(410,\"Search Earthquake Catalog\"),z(),H(411,\" to search the full earthquake catalog. After the search loads, a button will appear in the feed section with the chosen search parameters. \"),z(),N(412,\"p\"),H(413,\" If a specific search has already been made, click \"),N(414,\"b\"),H(415,\"Modify Search\"),z(),H(416,\" to search the earthquake catalog again. \"),z(),N(417,\"h4\"),H(418,\"Time Zone\"),z(),N(419,\"p\"),H(420,\" The time for the earthquakes displayed in this interface will be based on: \"),z(),N(421,\"ul\")(422,\"li\"),H(423,\" User Time Zone \\u2013 the time setting of your device. This may be incorrect depending on how your system's time zone is set up. \"),z(),N(424,\"li\"),H(425,\"UTC \\u2013 Universal Coordinated Time (similar to GMT)\"),z()(),N(426,\"h4\"),H(427,\"Distance\"),z(),N(428,\"p\"),H(429,\" The selected unit of distance (defaults to kilometers). The equation used for conversion is kilometers / 1.609 = miles (1 kilometer is equal to 0.621371 miles). The conversion from kilometers to miles is not exact and is rounded in some instances. \"),z(),N(430,\"ul\")(431,\"li\"),H(432,\"km - Kilometers\"),z(),N(433,\"li\"),H(434,\"mi - Miles\"),z()(),N(435,\"h4\"),H(436,\"Other Options\"),z(),N(437,\"p\"),H(438,\" The following options are available at the bottom of the settings panel. \"),z(),N(439,\"ul\")(440,\"li\"),H(441,\" Notifications are defaulted to ON, but can be toggled on or off. See the \"),N(442,\"b\"),H(443,\"Desktop Notifications\"),z(),H(444,\" expansion panel for more info. \"),z(),N(445,\"li\"),H(446,\" The \"),N(447,\"b\"),H(448,\"Install Application\"),z(),H(449,\" button is available for mobile devices to add the application to the device's home page. More details for installing on desktop and mobile can be found in the \"),N(450,\"b\"),H(451,\"Installing the Application\"),z(),H(452,\" expansion panel. \"),z(),N(453,\"li\"),H(454,\" The \"),N(455,\"b\"),H(456,\"Share Settings\"),z(),H(457,\" button copies the URL containing the search parameters on desktop. More details for sharing your settings for both mobile and desktop in the \"),N(458,\"b\"),H(459,\"Saving your Settings\"),z(),H(460,\" expansion panel below. \"),z()()()(),N(461,\"mat-expansion-panel\",0)(462,\"mat-expansion-panel-header\",1),$e(\"click\",function(){return r.onPanelHeaderClicked(r.panels.Notifications)}),N(463,\"mat-panel-title\"),H(464,\" Desktop Notifications \"),z()(),N(465,\"mat-panel-description\")(466,\"h4\",28),H(467,\"What to Expect\"),z(),N(468,\"p\"),H(469,\" Notifications alert you of new seismic events that have just occured. The notifications received are based on the selected feed in the settings menu. Notifications appear in the upper right-hand corner of your screen (when you have the application open in your browser or saved to your home screen). If the application is closed you will no longer receive notifications. Clicking on the notification will show the new earthquake in the application on your device. \"),z(),N(470,\"h4\",29),H(471,\" Enable or Disable Notifications \"),z(),N(472,\"p\"),H(473,\" Notifications can be enabled or disabled in the settings menu. Click the settings menu icon \"),rt(474,\"i\",6),H(475,' found in the upper right hand corner of the applicaiton. Scroll down to the \"Notifications\" section and select \"Desktop Notifications\" to toggle notifications on or off. '),z(),N(476,\"h4\",30),H(477,\"Browser Support\"),z(),N(478,\"p\"),H(479,\" Use the links below to learn how to enable/disable desktop notifications for your browser. \"),z(),N(480,\"ul\",31)(481,\"li\")(482,\"a\",32),H(483,\"Chrome\"),z()(),N(484,\"li\")(485,\"a\",33),H(486,\"Safari\"),z()(),N(487,\"li\")(488,\"a\",34),H(489,\"Edge\"),z()(),N(490,\"li\")(491,\"a\",35),H(492,\"Firefox\"),z()()()()(),N(493,\"mat-expansion-panel\",0)(494,\"mat-expansion-panel-header\",1),$e(\"click\",function(){return r.onPanelHeaderClicked(r.panels.Install)}),N(495,\"mat-panel-title\"),H(496,\" Installing the Application \"),z()(),N(497,\"mat-panel-description\")(498,\"h4\",36),H(499,\"Mobile\"),z(),N(500,\"p\"),H(501,\" To add the application to your home screen, do the following: \"),z(),N(502,\"ol\")(503,\"li\"),H(504,\" Tap the share button \"),rt(505,\"img\",37),z(),N(506,\"li\"),H(507,\"Scroll down and tap \"),N(508,\"b\"),H(509,\"Add to Home Screen\"),z()(),N(510,\"li\"),H(511,\"Tap \"),N(512,\"b\"),H(513,\"Add\"),z(),H(514,\" in the upper-right corner\"),z()(),N(515,\"p\"),H(516,\" You can now launch the application from your home screen by tapping on its icon. \"),z(),N(517,\"h4\",38),H(518,\"Desktop\"),z(),N(519,\"p\"),H(520,\"To add the application to your Desktop, do the following:\"),z(),N(521,\"ol\")(522,\"li\"),H(523,\" At the top right of the address bar, click Install \"),rt(524,\"img\",39),H(525,\". \"),z(),N(526,\"li\"),H(527,\"Follow the onscreen instructions to install the PWA.\"),z()()()(),N(528,\"mat-expansion-panel\",0)(529,\"mat-expansion-panel-header\",1),$e(\"click\",function(){return r.onPanelHeaderClicked(r.panels.Settings)}),N(530,\"mat-panel-title\"),H(531,\" Saving your Settings \"),z()(),N(532,\"mat-panel-description\")(533,\"p\"),H(534,\" The application is automatically saving your settings as you use the application. \"),z(),N(535,\"p\"),H(536,\" To share your settings you can either: \"),z(),N(537,\"ul\")(538,\"li\"),H(539,\" Copy the URL from your address bar. \"),z(),N(540,\"li\"),H(541,' Click the \"Share Settings\" button on the settings panel to copy the URL. '),z()(),N(542,\"p\"),H(543,\" To save your settings: \"),z(),N(544,\"ul\")(545,\"li\"),H(546,\" On mobile you can save the app to your home screen. \"),z(),N(547,\"li\"),H(548,\" Bookmark the page to save the application in its current state. \"),z()()()(),N(549,\"mat-expansion-panel\",0)(550,\"mat-expansion-panel-header\",1),$e(\"click\",function(){return r.onPanelHeaderClicked(r.panels.Missing)}),N(551,\"mat-panel-title\"),H(552,\" Missing Earthquakes \"),z()(),N(553,\"mat-panel-description\")(554,\"p\"),H(555,\" To answer the following questions: \"),z(),N(556,\"ul\")(557,\"li\"),H(558,\"Which events are in the list?\"),z(),N(559,\"li\"),H(560,\"Why are there \\u201Cmissing\\u201D earthquakes?\"),z(),N(561,\"li\"),H(562,\"There is an earthquake on another website; why is it not here?\"),z()(),N(563,\"p\"),H(564,\" The maps and lists show events which have been located by the USGS and contributing agencies within the last 30 days. They should not be considered to be complete lists of all events in the U.S. and adjacent areas and especially should not be considered to be complete lists of all events M4.5+ in the world. \"),z(),N(565,\"p\"),H(566,\" In most cases, we locate and report on earthquakes worldwide of magnitude 5.0 and larger in 30 minutes or less. Additionally, we locate and report on earthquakes magnitude 4.0 and larger within the contiguous U.S. and populated regions of Alaska within 30 minutes. Earthquakes of magnitude 2.0 or greater within the U.S. and populated regions of Alaska are often rapidly reported if they occur within the \"),N(567,\"a\",40),H(568,\"region of a contributing local seismic network\"),z(),H(569,\". \"),z(),N(570,\"p\"),H(571,\" We may not rapidly locate earthquakes smaller than 5.0 outside the U.S. unless they have caused significant damage or are widely felt. Earthquakes this small rarely cause significant damage. At times, some other agency may report an earthquake with a larger magnitude than what we compute from our data, especially for non-U.S. events near magnitude 5.0. If our magnitude for the event is less than magnitude 5.0, we may not issue a rapid report for it. \"),z(),N(572,\"p\"),H(573,\" Earthquakes occurring outside the U.S. and smaller than about magnitude 4.5 can be difficult for the USGS to locate if there are not enough data. The USGS continues to receive data from observatories throughout the world for several months after the events occur. Using those data, we add new events and revise existing events in later publications. For a description of these later publications and the data available, see \"),N(574,\"a\",41),H(575,\"Data\"),z(),H(576,\". \"),z(),N(577,\"p\"),H(578,\" There are many regional networks around the world that can record smaller earthquakes in their region than the NEIC global network can, and in many cases these regional networks do not share their data with the NEIC. So if you think there is a missing earthquake on our maps and lists, please see the national and regional links for the area of interest on these webpages: \"),z(),N(579,\"ul\")(580,\"li\")(581,\"a\",13),H(582,\"Earthquake Info by State/Territory\"),z()(),N(583,\"li\")(584,\"a\",42),H(585,\"Geophysics Institutions Throughout the World\"),z()()(),N(586,\"p\"),H(587,\"See also:\"),z(),N(588,\"ul\")(589,\"li\")(590,\"a\",43),H(591,\"FAQs about Latest Earthquake Information and Other Topics\"),z()()()()(),N(592,\"mat-expansion-panel\",0)(593,\"mat-expansion-panel-header\",1),$e(\"click\",function(){return r.onPanelHeaderClicked(r.panels.Report)}),N(594,\"mat-panel-title\"),H(595,\" Report an Earthquake \"),z()(),N(596,\"mat-panel-description\")(597,\"p\"),H(598,\" To report an earthquake you just felt, please use our \"),N(599,\"a\",44),H(600,\"Did You Feel It?\"),z(),H(601,\" form. \"),z()()(),N(602,\"mat-expansion-panel\",0)(603,\"mat-expansion-panel-header\",1),$e(\"click\",function(){return r.onPanelHeaderClicked(r.panels.Partners)}),N(604,\"mat-panel-title\"),H(605,\" USGS Partners \"),z()(),N(606,\"mat-panel-description\")(607,\"ul\",3)(608,\"li\")(609,\"i\"),rt(610,\"img\",45),z(),N(611,\"a\",46),H(612,\"ANSS - Advanced National Seismic System\"),z()(),N(613,\"li\",47)(614,\"i\"),rt(615,\"img\",48),z(),N(616,\"a\",49),H(617,\"Global Seismographic Network\"),z()(),N(618,\"li\",50)(619,\"i\"),rt(620,\"img\",51),z(),N(621,\"a\",52),H(622,\"NEHRP National Earthquake Hazards Reduction Program\"),z()()()()(),N(623,\"mat-expansion-panel\",0)(624,\"mat-expansion-panel-header\",1),$e(\"click\",function(){return r.onPanelHeaderClicked(r.panels.Contact)}),N(625,\"mat-panel-title\"),H(626,\" Contact Us \"),z()(),N(627,\"mat-panel-descri